Let $S$ denote the set of all continuous functions $f:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$ that satisfy the functional equation
\begin{align*}
f(x+y+f(xy))=f(x)+f(y)+xy,
\end{align*}
for all $x,y\in\mathbb{R}$.

If $f\in S$ and $f(0)=0$, prove that $f(x)=x^2$ for all $x\in\mathbb{R}$.
